<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate download time?", answer: "Convert the file size to bits (multiply bytes by 8) and divide by the speed in bits per second. For example, a 1 GB file is 8,589,934,592 bits. At 100 Mbps (100,000,000 bits per second), it takes about 85.9 seconds or roughly 1 minute 26 seconds to download. Real-world speeds are often lower due to overhead and network conditions." },
  { question: "What is the difference between Mbps and MBps?", answer: "Mbps (megabits per second) measures bandwidth/speed, while MBps (megabytes per second) measures data transfer rate. There are 8 bits in a byte, so 100 Mbps equals 12.5 MBps. Internet speeds are typically advertised in Mbps, while file sizes are shown in MB or GB (bytes). This distinction is important when estimating download times." },
  { question: "Why is my actual download speed slower than advertised?", answer: "Several factors reduce actual speed: network overhead (protocols add extra data), router/WiFi limitations, distance from the server, congestion on the network, and your ISP's traffic management. Typical real-world speeds are 60-80% of the advertised maximum. WiFi connections are generally slower than wired Ethernet connections." },
  { question: "How much bandwidth do I need for streaming?", answer: "For standard definition video: 3-5 Mbps. For HD (720p/1080p): 5-10 Mbps. For 4K/Ultra HD: 25-50 Mbps. For video calls: 3-5 Mbps up and down. These are per-stream requirements, so a household with multiple simultaneous users needs correspondingly more bandwidth. A 100 Mbps connection comfortably handles most household needs." },
  { question: "What is the difference between KB and KiB?", answer: "KB (kilobyte) commonly means 1,024 bytes in computing contexts (technically KiB in the IEC standard). In the SI standard, 1 KB is exactly 1,000 bytes. This calculator uses binary units where 1 KB = 1,024 bytes, 1 MB = 1,048,576 bytes, etc., which matches how operating systems typically report file sizes." }
]) %>

